00:03:16.959 --> 00:03:23.090
Eosin methylene blue agar is both a selective
and differential medium used for the detection

00:03:23.090 --> 00:03:26.170
and isolation of Gram-negative intestinal
pathogens.

00:03:26.170 --> 00:03:32.430
In Eosine methylene blue agar , Escherichia
coli- produce dark blue-black colonies with

00:03:32.430 --> 00:03:37.670
metallic green sheen indicating vigorous fermentation
of lactose and acid production.

00:03:37.670 --> 00:03:44.590
Enterobacter aerogenes- produce blue, dark-centered,
mucoid colonies indicating lactose fermentation

00:03:44.590 --> 00:03:46.430
and acid production.

00:03:46.430 --> 00:03:50.890
Macconkey agar, is selective for Gram negative
bacteria and can differentiate those bacteria

00:03:50.890 --> 00:03:56.140
that are able to ferment lactose .
Escherichia coli are Lactose fermenters and

00:03:56.140 --> 00:03:59.610
thereby appear pink
while Pseudomonas aeruginosa are Non lactose

00:03:59.610 --> 00:04:04.319
fermenters and appear colourless or Golden
colored.

00:04:04.319 --> 00:04:07.890
Hektoen enteric agar: Hektoen Enteric (HE)
Agar is a moderatively selective medium used

00:04:07.890 --> 00:04:14.450
for the isolation and cultivation of gram-negative
enteric microorganisms, especially Shigella

00:04:14.450 --> 00:04:19.259
and Salmonella from a variety of clinical
and nonclinical specimens.

00:04:19.259 --> 00:04:25.389
On HEA agar Shigella species develop into
green-colored colonies with darker blue-green

00:04:25.389 --> 00:04:32.050
centers. Salmonella species appear as blue-green
colonies with or without black centers.

